<TITLE> 2m Bangladeshi children acutely malnourished: UN </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 DHAKA, Mar 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Two million Bangladeshi children aged between six months and five years suffer from acute malnutrition, a UN study said on Sunday. Child malnutrition and households where people are going hungry remain major concerns for the country, it said. One in four households in Bangladesh is food insecure and out of the two million malnourished children, half a million are suffering from severe malnutrition, according to the survey by WFP, UNICEF and the Institute of Public Health Nutrition. "The situation of child malnutrition in this country is a silent emergency," UNICEF Representative Carel de Rooy said at the launch of the report. According to the survey, 58 percent of households said they had insufficient food in 2008 because of higher food prices. "Even if the prices of food are now falling, the crisis is far from being over," said John Aylieff, WFP Representative in Bangladesh. "The proportion of households' income that is now being spent on food is already higher than in 2005 and the impact of the global financial crisis on the poor is a major concern going forward." About half of Bangladesh's more than 140 million people live on less than $1 a day, officials 
